# Chronodel Data Analysis

The project that I am working on is to analyze the data of the Chronodel test, which is a test that measures the ability to perform a task in a delimation of time of 30 seconds. The data is collected from a sample of participants who have taken the test (n = 43). The goal of this analysis is to experiment the test Chronodel understand the distribution of the results and to compare the results of the Chronodel test with other tests that measure similar abilities, by others, i mean, Day Of the Week Backward and (DOTWB) and Month Of The Year Backward (MOTYB).

At the beggining of the analysis, we wanted to calculate the sensibility, specificity, positive predictive value and negative predictive value of the Chronodel test, but at the reception of the results, we saw, that there are a variability in the results of the Chronodel test, which is really low, and that the majority of the patients have a result of 1 on the Chronodel test, which means that they succeed the test, because we expected to have a more variability in the results, and also because we expected to have a lower success rate for the Chronodel test, so we decided to change our analysis plan and to focus on pourcentage of success for the three tests (DOTWB, MOTYB) to evaluate the coherence between the results and at the end, the distribution of the results for the three tests, to evaluate the variability and the ceiling effect.

```{r}
Data <- read.csv("ChronodelSansTNC_DATA_2026-03-30_1433.csv")
```

```{r}
# delete tle lines 11, 28 and 29 from the data
Data <- Data[-c(11, 28, 29), ]
```

The 3 subjects 11, 28 and 29 were removed from the data because they don't respect the general inclusion criteria of the study, witch is for a hypoacoustic for 11 and 28, for 29, he doesn't understand french language, and the test is in french, so we can't be sure that he understand the instructions of the test, it may appear some bias.

First of all we will analyze the concordance between the results of the DOTWB and MOTYB tests, which are represented by the variables "jour_reussite" and "mois_reussi" respectively. We will use the Kappa test to measure the agreement between these two variables.


```{r}
sum(complete.cases(Data[, c("jour_reussite", "mois_reussi")]))
```
To do the kappa test, we need to have complete cases for the variables "jour_reussite" and "mois_reussi", so we will check how many complete cases we have for these two variables. we have a total of 36 completes cases for these two variables, which is enough to do the Kappa test.

```{r}
# test of concordance for the variables "jour_reussite" and "mois_reussi"
library(irr)
kappa2(Data[, c("jour_reussite", "mois_reussi")])
```

As result of the Kappa test, we have a kappa value of 0.0859, that a really low value of agreement between the DOTWB and MOTYB tests. This suggest that the observed agreement is only slighty above ht would be expected by chance. This low Kappa value is likely explained by the highly unbalanced distribution of the data, with a majority of successful outcomes in the day-based test (ceiling effect), as well as the presence of discordant cases.

The p-value associated with the Kappa statistic was 0.204, which is above the conventional significance threshold of 0.05. Therefore, we fail to reject the null hypothesis (H0: κ = 0), meaning that there is no statistically significant agreement beyond chance between the two tests."


```{r}
# make a cross table to estimate the coherence between the results of the two tests
table(Data$jour_reussite, Data$mois_reussi, useNA = "no")
```


What we can see about the table is that 1 subject has failed both tests, witch mean that we have a negative concordance, we have 0 subject that has failed DOTWB and succeed MOTYB, we have an important asymetry, 13 subjects have succeed DOTWB and failed MOTYB a major discordance, and a the end, we have 22 subjects that have succeed both tests, which is a positive concordance.
We have a concordance of 22 + 1 = 23/36 = 63.89% of the subjects that have the same result in both tests, which is good concordance. But we have a discordance of 13/36 = 36.11% of the subjects that have different results in both tests, which is a huge discordance, that unbalance the concordance, and that explain the low kappa value that we have.

```{r}
taux_jour <- mean(Data$jour_reussite, na.rm = TRUE)
taux_mois <- mean(Data$mois_reussi, na.rm = TRUE)
taux_chrono <- mean(Data$chrono_reussi, na.rm = TRUE)

taux <- c(taux_jour, taux_mois, taux_chrono)

barplot(taux,
        names.arg = c("DOTWB", "MOTYB", "Chronodel"),
        ylim = c(0,1.1),
        ylab = ("success rate"),
        main = ("success rate for the three tests"),
        col = c("red", "blue", "green"))
text(x=1, y=taux_jour+0.05, labels=paste0(round(taux_jour*100, 2), "%"))
text(x=2, y=taux_mois+0.05, labels=paste0(round(taux_mois*100, 2), "%"))
text(x=3, y=taux_chrono+0.05, labels=paste0(round(taux_chrono*100, 2), "%"))
```


