The distribution of the results for the DOTWB test is really unbalanced, with a majority of successful outcomes, which suggest a ceiling effect. The distribution of the results for the MOTYB test is more balance, with 40% of "no" and 57.5% of "yes", which doesn't suggest a ceiling effect. The distribution of the results for the Chronodel test is really unbalanced, with all the subjects having a successful outcome, which suggest a ceiling effect. This ceiling effect can be explained by the fact that the tests are not challenging enough for the subjects.

```{r}
par(mfrow=c(1,3))

# Fonction pour éviter la répétition
plot_distribution <- function(var, title) {
  tab <- table(var, useNA = "no")
  prop <- tab / sum(tab)
  
  barplot(prop,
          main = title,
          ylim = c(0,1.1),
          col = c("red", "green"),
          names.arg = c("0", "1"))
  
  text(x = 1:2,
       y = prop + 0.05,
       labels = paste0(round(prop * 100, 2), "%"))
}

# DOTWB
plot_distribution(Data$jour_reussite, "Distribution DOTWB")

# MOTYB
